<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA53C5FFF6BBC15FE508724" blockId="3.[151,1437,577,819]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">
This species was described from the female 
<typeStatus id="54F167FBFFA53C5FFD73BC15FD67864C" box="[655,753,577,603]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">holotype</typeStatus>
and eight further females, taken in the rolled leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFA95BC15FEFE8668" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Dilleniaceae" genus="Hibbertia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dilleniales" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tontoutensis">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFA95BC15FEFE8668" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Hibbertia tontoutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFE8ABC31FD9E8697" box="[374,520,613,640]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Dilleniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dilleniales" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Dilleniaceae</taxonomicName>
] at Tontouta Valley not far from Noumea, 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA53C5FFC1FBC32FB028668" box="[995,1172,613,640]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
. In common with many species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFEF3BCDDFE3686B4" baseAuthorityName="ThripsWiki" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[271,416,649,675]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFEF3BCDDFE3686B4" box="[271,416,649,675]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Teuchothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the maxillary stylets are long, but they are particularly close together medially (
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA53C5FFAD3BCDDFAE386B4" box="[1327,1397,649,675]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Heads of paratypes of Teuchothrips species. (1) cleistanthi; (2) kraussi; (3) ornatus; (4) noumeaensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405146/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It seems to be very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA53C5FFE2EBCFAFDD386D0" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1993" box="[466,581,686,711]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA53C5FFE2EBCFAFDD386D0" box="[466,581,686,711]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">T. ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has a curious sculptured area medially on the postoccipital ridge of the head, and the pronotal anteromarginal setae are longer with the posteroangular setae shorter. It remains known only from the type series, of which 
<specimenCount id="9D4C12D0FFA53C5FFE16BCA1FDFD8718" box="[490,619,757,783]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" type="female">four female</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="9D4C12D0FFA53C5FFD5DBCA2FC908718" box="[673,774,757,784]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
<typeStatus id="54F167FBFFA53C5FFCF1BCA2FCEE8707" box="[781,888,758,784]" pageId="3" pageNumber="241">paratypes</typeStatus>
were studied on loan from the Museum National d’Histoire Naturelle, Paris.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
